<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-757-348  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 757 348.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  August 19 1990 v139 p1(N) p1(L) 26 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Washington is relaxing its stand on guarding computer security.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Markoff, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Pres Bush reverses a Reagan Administration effort to controlaccess to computerized information.andP;  The Reagan Administration hadestablished a central office within the National Security Agency(NSA) - the National Computer Security Center - to set standardsfor the security of both Federal and private computers.andP;  Access todatabases, collections of commercial satellite photographs andinformation compiled by university researchers would berestricted.andP;  The purpose was to prevent foreign countries frompiecing together sensitive information.andP;  Civil libertariansworried, fearing limits on the free flow of information, and somelawmakers and computer industry officials were concerned aboutpossible abuses of power by the NSA.andP;  Congress passed legislationin 1987 opposing the administration's policy, and now, Pres Bushhas signed a memorandum revising the Reagan Administration'sorders and disbanding the NSA's security center.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Security AgencySecurityNational GovernmentInformation Storage and RetrievalData basesUnited StatesUnited States. National Computer Security CenterInformation Services.andO;Person:    Bush, George (social policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>